article.description:
Kendra Wecker had 23 points and 13 rebounds
and Nicole Ohlde added 18 points as No. 5 Kansas State beat Baylor
65-53 Saturday.
article.headline: Wecker fuels Kansas State with 23 points, 13 boards
article.linkText: Kansas State starts slow, finishes fast vs. Baylor
article.story:
WACO, Texas (AP) -- Kansas State's Kendra Wecker warmed up just
in time Saturday against Baylor.

	   Wecker scored 14 of her 23 points in the second half -- including
eight during a crucial late run -- as No. 5 Kansas State beat Baylor
65-53.

	   "Kendra is learning more and more what it takes to compete at
an All-American level,'' Kansas State coach Deb Patterson said.
"At crunch time, you have to make your presence known. It's easy
when you're clicking on all cylinders, but it's challenging when
things don't go well.''

	   Kansas State (21-2, 8-1 Big 12) led 24-23 at halftime, then
opened the second half with a 10-2 run keyed by 3-pointers from
Chelsea Domenico and Amy Dutmer.

	   But Baylor (15-6, 4-5) cut the deficit to 42-41 with nine
minutes left on Sophia Young's three-point play. Then Jessika
Stratton converted a one-and-one to put Baylor up 43-42.

	   Nicole Ohlde hit a layup and Wecker scored eight points during
the Wildcats' 12-6 run that put them up 55-48 with 2:48 left.
Wecker finished 8-for-27 from the field, including 3-for-14 from
3-point range, and had 13 rebounds.

	   "In those final five minutes, I tried not to be timid,'' Wecker
said. "I rushed things in the first half. I finally calmed down
and had the guts to step up when I needed it.''

	   Baylor narrowed the margin to 57-52 with a little over a minute
remaining, but the Wildcats went 6-for-6 from the line in the final
30 seconds to put the game away. Stratton led Baylor with 11
points.

	   "We couldn't score when it counted,'' Stratton said. "Kansas
State is so well-rounded inside and outside. They made the big
shots down the stretch, and we didn't.''

	   Both teams struggled from the floor in the first half, with
Kansas State going 10-for-31 and Baylor going 8-for-31.
